\begin_layout Subsection*
2.8.
 Hough Transform
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Hough transform is a feature extraction technique used in image analysis,
 computer vision, and digital image processing.The purpose of the technique
 is to find imperfect instances of objects within a certain class of shapes
 by a voting procedure.
 The classical Hough transform was concerned with the identification of
 lines in the image, but later the Hough transform has been extended to
 identifying positions of arbitrary shapes, most commonly circles or ellipses.
 Here we specify 
\begin_inset Formula $rgb2gray$
\end_inset

 as colorspace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
2.8.1.
 Lines extraction using Hough Transform
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To extract lines using Hough transform, click on the arrow then choose 
\begin_inset Formula $Lines\,extraction$
\end_inset

 inside the 
\begin_inset Formula $HoughTransform$
\end_inset

 box.
 See the result in figure 9
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
2.8.2.
 Circles extraction using Hough Transform
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To extract lines using Hough transform, click on the arrow then choose 
\begin_inset Formula $Circles\,extraction$
\end_inset

 inside the 
\begin_inset Formula $HoughTransform$
\end_inset

 box.
 See the result in figure 9
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 9: Lines extraction and Circles extraction using Hough Transform
\end_layout

